<Center>

## Logical Reasoning using Punched Cards

</Center>

*Need Intro*

### Binary System

The five bulbs, Yellow, Pink, Red, Green, and Blue, are represented by the five holes, which in turn represent binary digits. Each 1 (or U slit hole) corresponds to a true term; each 0 (or O hole), to a false term. Each card is a unique combination of true and false terms, and since the 32 cards exhaust all possible combinations, they are the equivalent of what is called a "truth table" for the five terms.

The operation of the cards is explained by showing how they can be used for solving a problem in two-valued logic. We can start by taking case 1, which contains 8 cards and focusing only on Red, Green, and Blue light. Three statements are given containing simple assertions and negation statements. The aim is to determine which bulbs are on or off among these.

To solve this problem, start with the punch cards in any order. Only three terms are involved, so we shall be concerned with only the R, G, and B holes.

<Center>

<table border="1" cellpadding="8" cellspacing="0">
<tr><th>Symbol</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
<tr><td>R</td><td>Red bulb is 'ON'</td></tr>
<tr><td>R̅</td><td>Red bulb is 'OFF'</td></tr>
<tr><td>G</td><td>Green bulb is 'ON'</td></tr>
<tr><td>G̅</td><td>Green bulb is 'OFF'</td></tr>
<tr><td>B</td><td>Blue bulb is 'ON'</td></tr>
<tr><td>B̅</td><td>Blue bulb is 'OFF'</td></tr>
</table>

</Center>

### Case 1: RGB (with 8 cards only)

**Statements:**

A. The red bulb is 'ON'

B. The blue bulb is 'OFF'

C. 'ON' bulb only has 'OFF' Neighbour

The problem has three statements. The first statement, A, "The red bulb is 'ON'," tells us that the combination R̅XX cards is not permitted, so we must eliminate all cards bearing this combination. It is done as follows. Insert the stick in the R position and lift. The stick will raise all cards bearing R̅ cards, the invalid combination, so these cards are discarded. All remaining cards are assembled into a pack once more (in any order), and we are ready for the second statement.

<question multiplechoice>
csq_prompt = "After performing an action using Statement A, how many cards are left in the pack?"
csq_options = ["8", "4", "2", "1"]
csq_soln = "4"
</question>

The second statement, B, "The blue bulb is 'OFF'," tells us that the combination XXB cards is not permitted, so we must eliminate all cards bearing this combination. Similarly to the statement A, insert the stick in the B position and lift. The stick will raise all cards bearing B̅ cards, the valid combination, so these cards we need to keep; the cards in our hands need to be discarded. All remaining cards are assembled into a pack once more (in any order), and we are ready for the third statement.
